			<h5 class="case-study-title">Branding</h5>
		</div>
		<div class="pull-right big-block">
			<p>
				For the branding of this product we felt the need to be the most descriptive as possible with its function, so we tried to represent an air wave transporting particles. The colors of the particles are the reflect of the existing standard scale at national level for the measurement of level of contamination and purity levels in the air. As the standard dictates, the green tones indicate purity, the yellow and orange indicate caution meanwhile we wanted to use the blue ones to give more live and to represent the air itself.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="case-study-block container">
		<div class="pull-left small-block">
			<h5 class="case-study-title">Design</h5>
		</div>
		<div class="pull-right big-block">
			<p>
				It was important to us that this were a very user-centered application. We did not want it to feel like this was an enterprise or government app, which could drive users away.
			</p>
			<p>
				So we used clear backgrounds with life full pictures and very explicit icons according to the contingency level or the given alert.
			</p>
			<p>
				We created a very colorful but simple design, that included pictures of Nuevo Leon's landmarks as background, but being careful in not including any official state government's colors or branding to make sure the app was not linked to the government in a heavy way.
			</p>
		</div>
